1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:27,185
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambho Darsah Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambho Darsah Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambho Darsah

2
00:00:27,722 --> 00:00:31,847
homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:34,390 --> 00:00:53,310
So the next perfection, it began, remember, with dana, giving, morality, sila, and then renunciation, nikamma, wisdom, panya is the next one.

4
00:00:54,491 --> 00:00:56,734
So now, panya,

5
00:00:57,658 --> 00:01:02,265
spelled P-A-N-N with that Spanish symbol on top.

6
00:01:02,284 --> 00:01:03,807
I forget the name of it.

7
00:01:03,826 --> 00:01:04,408
Does anybody know it?

8
00:01:04,828 --> 00:01:06,171
Spanish symbol.

9
00:01:07,653 --> 00:01:08,453
And the A.

10
00:01:09,936 --> 00:01:18,266
And this paña, it's got that root sound, ñ, which comes right through the Greek, gn,

11
00:01:18,549 --> 00:01:40,254
and comes to us as knowledge and the pā is a sort of giving it a real power so there's two words vijñāna it comes to the same word which means sort of discern or discriminate and paññā means to sort of really see deeply so we translate that as insight

12
00:01:41,212 --> 00:01:53,326
Now it has both the active form as an insightful moment but it also has a passive form as wisdom, your collected wisdom.

13
00:01:53,828 --> 00:01:56,090
And remember wisdom is not to be confused with knowledge.

14
00:01:56,932 --> 00:02:02,058
Wisdom is to do with how we relate to the world.

15
00:02:02,638 --> 00:02:07,203
It's a much bigger word than just knowledge.

16
00:02:07,183 --> 00:02:10,408
And the Buddha talks about three stages.

17
00:02:10,769 --> 00:02:19,681
The first one is sutta-merpanya, which is the understanding or the insights you get from listening to somebody, as you are now.

18
00:02:22,145 --> 00:02:33,562
And if you think about it, that's how you enter into anything, whether it's a secular subject like science or history.

19
00:02:33,862 --> 00:02:50,168
and it's a spiritual path first of all you listen you receive something so it's the wisdom you get from receiving something and this is can be just an intellectual understanding you know oh yes it's very interesting but it can also strike quite deeply

20
00:02:50,519 --> 00:03:02,442
And there are occasions in the scripture where people just on hearing a scripture seem to have had a quite deep insight just on the hearing of it.

21
00:03:03,022 --> 00:03:08,973
So, listening to something can be quite life-changing.

22
00:03:10,015 --> 00:03:13,842
Maybe there is something that you have experienced.

23
00:03:13,823 --> 00:03:23,917
In my own life, I would say the experience of actually not so much reading, but seeing, waiting for God, though.

24
00:03:23,937 --> 00:03:28,082
I can always consider that the beginning of my spiritual path.

25
00:03:28,103 --> 00:03:30,246
It had such a profound effect on me.

26
00:03:30,847 --> 00:03:34,211
And I couldn't stop talking about it for days, to the annoyance of everybody who knew me.

27
00:03:35,034 --> 00:03:38,883
And that wasn't as though I thought about it or anything.

28
00:03:38,924 --> 00:03:44,197
I was just receiving the basic message that that play had to give.

29
00:03:44,737 --> 00:03:46,782
Just hitting it at the right time in the right place.

30
00:03:48,669 --> 00:03:51,032
The next one is cinta mea panea.

31
00:03:51,614 --> 00:03:53,256
Cinta is just the word for the mind.

32
00:03:53,276 --> 00:03:57,981
So that's basically when we receive something, we begin to mull it over in our minds.

33
00:03:58,782 --> 00:04:01,406
And in so doing, as it were, it becomes our own knowledge.

34
00:04:02,086 --> 00:04:08,534
So that's why you get what we call inspirational reading.

35
00:04:08,514 --> 00:04:20,468
In inspirational reading, and this is something that the Benedictines in the Christian tradition developed, it's called Lectio Divino, divine reading.

36
00:04:20,488 --> 00:04:23,858
You read something, that's your receiving, that's your receiving.

37
00:04:24,394 --> 00:04:31,024
And then, as it were, when something strikes you, a bit like music, a bit like a poem, you keep repeating it.

38
00:04:31,264 --> 00:04:38,795
You keep sort of just reading it over and over until you get this sense of absorbing it, sort of a digestion.

39
00:04:39,958 --> 00:04:46,166
And at that point, maybe not immediately afterwards, but at some time you find yourself thinking about it.

40
00:04:47,129 --> 00:04:49,913
And this thinking about it actually makes it your own knowledge.

41
00:04:50,550 --> 00:04:58,701
Now, if you can't think about it, it never actually gets to be your own knowledge, and you normally can't explain it.

42
00:04:59,281 --> 00:05:01,605
I have a very good personal example of that.

43
00:05:01,625 --> 00:05:09,035
I've read relativity theory in a very simple layman's terms many a time, but I still can't explain it to somebody.

44
00:05:10,076 --> 00:05:14,701
I seem to lose the thread of the logic of it at some point.

45
00:05:16,285 --> 00:05:17,666
But I understand it when I read it.

46
00:05:18,427 --> 00:05:19,329
This is the funny thing.

47
00:05:19,689 --> 00:05:24,095
But when I try and think about it, I sort of tend to lose it.

48
00:05:26,737 --> 00:05:30,021
And then finally, of course, there's this vipassanamaya paññā.

49
00:05:30,242 --> 00:05:35,387
So seeing things at that direct grasp of things.

50
00:05:36,168 --> 00:05:45,060
And that, of course, is really beginning to employ a faculty within us which is not thought.

51
00:05:45,478 --> 00:06:10,744
So this faculty within us, paññā, this intuitive wisdom, this intuitive intelligence, intuitive awareness is sometimes called, but if we just sort of separate it from awareness, which is more the receiving part, the actual, the bit that's intelligent, the intuitive intelligence, normally speaking, does not distinguish itself from thought.

52
00:06:12,495 --> 00:06:36,545
and the whole process of vipassana is to begin to separate that intelligence from thought and that in the Mahāsī tradition is done by noting so the thought is contained in a word but as it were the intelligence is pointing at something else the direct feeling of a thing or the direct characteristic of a thing such as its arising and passing nature

53
00:06:37,521 --> 00:07:05,418
and in so doing in freeing itself from thought it now has a direct grasp of the way things really are and the paradox is that it couldn't have got to that point without going through that process of receiving knowledge and thinking about it and it's through that very medium of thought that once it's had an insight it can then tell itself what it's just seen

54
00:07:07,086 --> 00:07:10,471
Otherwise, it wouldn't be able to reflect upon the insights that it has.

55
00:07:11,394 --> 00:07:19,005
And I think the greatest example of that in scientific history, or the most common one, or the most famous one, is Archimedes.

56
00:07:20,108 --> 00:07:33,228
So Archimedes is trying to figure out whether this crown is real gold or not, and he needs the weight and the volume, and he divides one into the other, or he gets confused, and eventually comes up with a specific weight, and then he knows it's pure gold.

57
00:07:34,137 --> 00:07:37,139
When it comes to weight of an irregular object, there's no problem.

58
00:07:37,259 --> 00:07:39,742
He just puts it on weights and he knows how many grams it is.

59
00:07:40,923 --> 00:07:43,084
But how do you get the volume of an irregular shape?

60
00:07:43,925 --> 00:07:45,466
Now, to us, of course, it seems very obvious.

61
00:07:45,687 --> 00:07:47,928
But in those days, somebody's got to crack that.

62
00:07:48,168 --> 00:07:52,031
Somebody's got to actually break through that conundrum.

63
00:07:52,793 --> 00:07:55,055
How do you get the volume of an irregular shape?

64
00:07:55,615 --> 00:07:58,458
So he's thinking about it and he's probably racking his brains about it.

65
00:07:58,778 --> 00:08:01,040
The king would probably chop his head off.

66
00:08:01,060 --> 00:08:03,721
And finally, he gives up and he takes a bath.

67
00:08:04,394 --> 00:08:20,670
and as he's relaxing, I can only presume he's relaxing, not thinking about it, getting into a bath, and as he gets into the bath, he suddenly sees that the water is rising, and it must be rising by the displacement caused through his own body.

68
00:08:21,492 --> 00:08:24,896
And there he is, he's got it, and he shouts, Eureka, I've got it, I've found it.

69
00:08:25,916 --> 00:08:33,404
If he'd never have had a bath at that moment, we probably would still not know how to get the volume of an irregular shape.

70
00:08:33,857 --> 00:08:58,245
so that ability that we have within us, this intuitive intelligence is what Vipassana meditation is specifically trying to develop and that's how we get these insights and the insight remember into impermanence, into the psychology of suffering

71
00:08:58,342 --> 00:09:05,955
and into this quality of not-me-not-mine, you see, is liberational.

72
00:09:05,975 --> 00:09:10,881
That's what actually liberates us from a delusive idea of what the world is.

73
00:09:11,602 --> 00:09:15,548
And it's that liberation which brings us to perfect peace and happiness.

74
00:09:16,610 --> 00:09:27,287
So, this, so pāññā, of course, is absolutely central to the Buddha's teaching and how to develop it and where to look in order to liberate ourselves.

75
00:09:29,798 --> 00:09:59,501
and therefore that also is a perfection that also has to be brought to a point of keen exercise I can only hope my words have been of some assistance may you develop your paññā and be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later Sādhu, Sādhu, Sādhu

